<h2 id="when-to-use">When to Use Each</h2>

<p><strong>Choose OpenAI GPT-4.1 fine-tuning when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>You need the highest-quality base model and budget is not the primary constraint.</li>
  <li>Your application already uses the OpenAI API and you want to minimise integration surface.</li>
  <li>You need multi-agent / multi-turn conversation datasets with named participants.</li>
  <li>You want to serve the fine-tuned model through OpenAI's hosted inference without managing infrastructure.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Choose Claude fine-tuning when:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Training budget is tight and Claude 3 Haiku's lower per-token cost materially changes your economics.</li>
  <li>Your use case requires long-context fidelity — Claude has a larger native context window.</li>
  <li>You are building on Anthropic's Constitutional AI safety layer and want that preserved in the fine-tune.</li>
  <li>You are already integrated with the Anthropic API and want to keep one API dependency.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="checklist">Pre-submit Checklist</h2>

<p>Run through this before uploading either dataset:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Every line is valid JSON (no trailing commas, no comments).</li>
  <li>Every object has a top-level <code>messages</code> key.</li>
  <li>Every message has <code>role</code> and <code>content</code>; <code>content</code> is a non-empty string.</li>
  <li>First message role is <code>system</code> (required for Claude, best practice for OpenAI).</li>
  <li>Last message role is <code>assistant</code>.</li>
  <li>No unsupported fields: check your provider's current schema — it changes.</li>
  <li>Dataset has at least 10 examples.</li>
  <li>No example exceeds the provider's max token limit per example.</li>
</ul>

<p>The <a href="/">DataPrep Convert tab</a> validates all of these automatically against the provider preset you select. Paste your dataset, pick the preset, and errors surface inline with line numbers.</p>

